The Path to Nuclear Disarmament
NEW YORK – Mass destruction weapons and disarmament represent one of the most difficult challenges the world faces today. One of my priorities as UN Secretary-General is to promote the global common good and find solutions to problems that know no borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is a matter of the highest importance for the common good.
My interest in this issue is partly based on personal experiences.
My home country, South Korea, has suffered from the devastation of conventional warfare and has been threatened by nuclear weapons and other mass destruction weapons.
Yet such threat scenarios exist not only in Asia.
Although the use of nuclear weapons has long been considered taboo, disarmament remains merely an aspiration.
Is a taboo that applies only to the use of such weapons really sufficient?
When it comes to nuclear weapons, individual states make the most important decisions.
Yet the UN plays a crucial role in this process.
We offer a central forum in which states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and inform in order to achieve our agreed goals, and we advocate for them.
Most states have decided to forgo nuclear weapons and have summarized their commitments under the Non-Proliferation Treaty.
Yet some states view such weapons as a status symbol, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against an attack with nuclear weapons, which mainly explains the estimated 26,000 weapons that still exist.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and creating new risks that nuclear weapons will be used.
The world is still concerned about nuclear activities in North Korea and Iran, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns through peaceful means.
There are also concerns that a "nuclear renaissance" is looming, as nuclear energy is viewed as a clean energy alternative during times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this will lead to the production and use of more nuclear material that must be protected from proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are enormous.
Yet the costs and risks of their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve.
Think about the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm Institute for International Peace Research), military spending reached over $1.3 trillion last year.
A decade ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating the total cost of nuclear weapons alone in the United States at over $5.8 trillion, including future cleanup costs.
This is a huge investment that could have been used for many other productive purposes.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and their inherent dangers have sparked a global idea movement on how to give nuclear disarmament new life.
We have witnessed the UN Disarmament Commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition, and Norway's Seven Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan have established the International Commission on Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Civil society groups and nuclear-armed states have also proposed initiatives, such as the Hoover Plan introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own Five-Point Plan.
First: I call on all members of the Non-Proliferation Treaty, especially the nuclear powers, to fulfill their obligations under the treaty and to engage in negotiations on effective measures that lead to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they could negotiate a nuclear weapons convention supported by a strong control system, as has long been proposed by the UN.
I have sent a draft of such a convention, which provides a good starting point, to all UN member states.
The nuclear powers should actively engage with this issue together with other states at the UN Disarmament Conference in Geneva, the only multilateral negotiating forum for disarmament in the world.
The world would welcome the resumption of bilateral negotiations between the United States and Russia, with the aim of substantially and verifiably disarming their arsenals.
Governments should also invest more in nuclear control research and development.
Britain's proposal to hold a conference of nuclear powers on the topic of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Second: The permanent members of the Security Council should begin discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly convey to states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not be victims of a nuclear weapon use or threat.
The Council could also call for a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not members of the Non-Proliferation Treaty should stop their nuclear weapons programs and undertake their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: Unilateral moratoriums on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials should only be allowed to a limited extent.
We need new efforts to bring the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty into force, as well as encouragement for the Disarmament Conference to immediately and without conditions commence talks on a treaty on fissile materials.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly endorse efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
Furthermore, I urge all members of the Non-Proliferation Treaty to urgently conclude their security agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily introduce the stricter security clauses of the Additional Protocol.
Fourthly: Nuclear powers often circulate descriptions of what they do to achieve these goals.
Yet these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like the nuclear powers to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and contribute to their further dissemination.
The fact that there is no significant estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons confirms the need for greater transparency.
And finally, various supplementary measures are required.
These include the elimination of other types of weapons of mass destruction, new efforts against terrorism with weapons of mass destruction, a limitation of the production and trade of conventional weapons, and new weapon bans, among others for missiles and space weapons.
If there are real, confirmed progress in disarmament, the ability to eliminate the nuclear threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the deadliest weapons in the world and their components, we make it more difficult to carry out terrorist attacks with weapons of mass destruction.
These proposals offer a new beginning, not only for disarmament, but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
